    {
      "id": "pYjpcEWvijFdgtodThxqo",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1110.3575522963913,
      "y": 4379.777406282435,
      "width": 1547.0587158203125,
      "height": 150,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1L",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 244283938,
      "version": 150,
      "versionNonce": 727648574,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1783944821516,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "- HLS is an adaptive streaming protocol where the server stores multiple encoded versions of the same video at different bitrates (2Mbps, 5Mbps, ...etc). \n- Each version is divided into small segments(seg1, seg2, se3, ...), and a master playlist(.m3u8) tells the client what qualities are available. \n- The player downloads the playlist first, then requests video segments one by one. \n- After every segment, it estimates network bandwidth and buffer health and decides which quality to request next.  \n- Because all renditions are time-aligned, it can switch between qualities seamlessly.\n - This approach minimizes buffering, enables adaptive bitrate streaming, and works efficiently with CDNs because everything is delivered over standard HTTP.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "- HLS is an adaptive streaming protocol where the server stores multiple encoded versions of the same video at different bitrates (2Mbps, 5Mbps, ...etc). \n- Each version is divided into small segments(seg1, seg2, se3, ...), and a master playlist(.m3u8) tells the client what qualities are available. \n- The player downloads the playlist first, then requests video segments one by one. \n- After every segment, it estimates network bandwidth and buffer health and decides which quality to request next.  \n- Because all renditions are time-aligned, it can switch between qualities seamlessly.\n - This approach minimizes buffering, enables adaptive bitrate streaming, and works efficiently with CDNs because everything is delivered over standard HTTP.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    }
  ],
